President Uhuru Kenyatta left the country on Friday evening for Beijing to attend the Forum on China-Africa Cooperation. The plane carrying the Head of State and his delegation departed from Jomo Kenyatta International Airport shortly after 7 pm. Leader of Majority Aden Duale, Head of Public Service Joseph Kinyua and Chief of Defence Forces General Samson Mwathethe led senior government officials in seeing off the President. Besides the FOCAC Summit, Uhuru is expected to hold bilateral talks with his host, President Xi Jinping focused on trade, infrastructure, investments, education and technology. Uhuru travels to China a day after meeting with British Prime Minister Theresa May in Nairobi and shortly after returning from the US where he met President Donald Trump. While addressing a joint press conference with PM Theresa May in Nairobi on Thursday, the President said Kenya will follow realistic cooperation with all global partners that have reciprocal interests. The goal of the 2018 FOCAC meeting is the promotion of economic and trade cooperation between China and African economies. Click here for the latest political news